Just came across an odd bug:
If I have this CSS HubSpot combines it into one single padding function
```padding-top: var(--padTop);
padding-bottom: var(--padBottom);
padding-left: var(--padLeft);
padding-right: var(--padRight);```
becomes:
```padding:var(--padTop) var(--padRight) var(--padBottom) var(--padLeft);```
At first this seems fine, but now look at the case where the var --padBottom is not set, due to the way CSS vars work the entire statement fails, the workaround is to add a backup of 0 however it’s not the same as just letting a single statement fail completely

As I said you could set a fallback of 0 but what if I want the expression to fail so it can fallback to a value set on a different decleration e.g.

```.myclass {
padding:10px;
}

.myclass {
padding-left:var(--paddingLEFT); /* If - padding left is not set the padding left will be 10px, if padding left has a default of 0 it will be 0 */
}```

Does it still condense it if you use logical properties?
```.myclass {
  padding-block: var(--padding-top) var(--padding-bottom);
  padding-inline: var(--padding-left) var(--padding-right);
}```
or
```.myclass {
  padding-block-end: var(--padding-bottom);
  padding-block-start: var(--padding-top);
  padding-inline-start: var(--padding-left);
  padding-inline-end: var(--padding-right);
}```
I believe that the logical versions of those properties technically have different behaviors than the padding shorthand _(in cases where you switch language directions)_, so they shouldn’t get condensed by a minifier.
